Text: My individual role/goal for this week was to work on extracting the relevant variables from the NZ greyhound racing website.
I had a personal goal to populate our shared database by the end of this week.
This was so that my team would not have to wait too long to use the historical and current data to implement their portion of the project.
We had last met altogether on Friday (proposal presentation) and divided out our tasks accordingly.
I was extracting data of structured (tabular) and unstructured (text) type from one website.
The goal was to wrangle the data so that it was more meaningful for (potential) statistical reasons and that it would match SQL syntax for querying.
To judge my progress, I would one-by-one tick off the variables given in Kevin's handout.
I felt as though I was pursuing great progress as I had ticked off the variables one by one.
What worked well was my individual progress.
However, as I was doing this, I had also thought of things in terms of our clients needs that I needed to converse with my team about.
One thing my team and I need to work on is our lack of face-to-face meeting.
As mentioned, the last time we met in person as a group was the Friday.
Since I was querying the tables through R, I wanted to start planning my script for querying based off our entity-relationship diagram.
This was a task one of my other teammates had to do.
I had asked her to perhaps screenshot what she has done so I could plan - however, their was a part of the task missing.
Despite this, I decided to add the missing portion myself because I just thought it would be easier than asking her to do so.
Come Thursday, I felt burned out and some of my group members were not happy with this particular team members contribution.
Ultimately my other team member had to pick up the slack.
In retrospect, I did not message her to fix or add to her task because I thought that if I just quickly implemented what I needed, I would get results faster.
It would have been beneficial to the rest of the team and I if I had just asked her - but at the end of the day, I didn't want to step on anyones toes, especially since we are all equal team members.
I think next time it would be beneficial if we lay out team expectations earlier on.

For now, a conversation about performance and expectations would be useful in our next team meeting so that everyone is on the same page and is given a chance to pull their weight or help us understand their lack of contribution.
Despite the hiccup, most of my team members are awesome people with a can-do attitude.
Our team dynamic is very much always open-dialogue, which is very important to me for effective team work - although it may need a little work.
A personal achievement was that I had successfully utilised the skills and knowledge I had gain in semester one.
I now have an R script that can be used to extract the historical and current greyhound racing data off of the website and queried into MySQL.
Using some data science skills made me feel accomplished because I had questioned whether I would be any good as a Data Analyst.
At least now I know I can be (half) okay and continue to develop my confidence.
I have been wanting to explore some Kaggle datasets to test my skills and undergo a personal project.
Although I am not quite confident yet, I at least now feel a little more confident before coming into this project.
However, still a long way to go in terms of personal development.
This project has been pretty stressful for me that I have essentially abandoned my INFO204 paper to work on it.
One thing I do need to change next week is to shift some of my energy into studying for my INFO204 paper - which will help me develop my data science skills.
Overall, my individual project goals for next week is to finally populate our shared database so that my team members can start implementing their portion of the project.
We are currently waiting for some validation on our ERD plan before we do this.
I also want to explore some PHP/node.JS web scraping automation tools so that our deliverables could possibly be close to executable.
A million and one tasks to be completed!
